			<ns0:name>ncb...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/100032148147647801554/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">SCons provides an &amp;quot;entrypoint&amp;quot; script that searches for SCons in the expected locations, and in fact gives priority over any location in the Python path.  This means that if there is any version of SCons installed on a system, it will be used in preference to the version of SCons in the third_party directory.  In of itself this is not a problem, but version skew can result in bugs / incompatibilities.

For example, I encountered a bug where the compiler could not find the &amp;quot;ppapi_cpp&amp;quot; library.  On closer examination, library paths were not being passed to the compiler because of a data corruption bug similar to the following:
http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1217

As it turned out, I had SCons 1.2.0 installed on my system, which is susceptible to this bug when used with Python 2.6, and the entry point script was choosing the older, installed version of SCons.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-06-17T20:28:15.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-06-17T18:39:20.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
